Content.Question:
duck

Content.Answer:
duck - A swimming bird of the genus Anas and kindred genera of the family Anatidae, of which species are found all over the world.
This is the main current sense

1863 C. Kingsley, Water-babies “Then he..turned up his eyes like a duck in thunder.”

1894 J. D. Astley, Fifty Years of my Life “I always took to shooting like a duck to water.”

Content.Answer: duck - In phrases and proverbial sayings. duck's weather, fine day for ducks, etc., referring to wet weather; like a duck in thunder, like a (dying) duck in a thunderstorm: having a forlorn and hopeless appearance; like water off (or from) a duck's back, like (or as) a duck (takes) to water: easily, readily; does (or will, would) a duck swim?: a colloquial phrase of enthusiastic acceptance or confirmation.

Content.Question:
ducks

1849 W. M. Thackeray, Pendennis “They must be young Pendennis's white ducks.”

Content.Question:
duck

1944 , Hansard Commons “The marvellous American invention, the ‘Duck’, spelt D.U.K.W., is a heavy lorry which goes at between 40 and 50 miles per hour along the road, and can plunge into the water and swim out for miles to sea in quite choppy weather.”

1945 , Manch. Guardian “Officially known as ‘Dukws’—a combination of the factory serial letters D for boat, U for lorry body, and KW for lorry chassis—they quickly became known in the Army and Navy as ‘Ducks’.”

1945 , Ann. Reg. 1944 “‘Ducks’, amphibious lorries which were equally at home on land and in the water.”

1958 , Observer “Supply craft might stand offshore and disgorge their cargoes into ducks and other smaller craft.”
Content.Answer:
duck - An amphibious vehicle (see quots.).
This is the main current sense

duck

duck - A swimming bird of the genus Anas and kindred genera of the family Anatidae, of which species are found all over the world.
This is the main current sense

duck

duck

1842 S. Lover, Handy Andy “‘What do you say..will you dine with me?’ ‘Will a duck swim?’ chuckled out Jack Horan.”

1863 C. Kingsley, Water-babies “Then he..turned up his eyes like a duck in thunder.”

1867 A. D. Richardson, Beyond Mississippi “He takes to them as instinctively as a young duck to water.”

1891 L. T. Meade, Sweet Girl Graduate “‘Do you really think that Maggie Oliphant cares for Mr. Hammond?’..‘Cares for him!.. Does a duck swim? Does a baby like sweet things?’”

1893 , Scribner's Mag. “She has taken to society as a duck takes to water.”

1894 J. D. Astley, Fifty Years of my Life “I always took to shooting like a duck to water.”

1906 ‘O. Henry’, Four Million “‘With you, Dempsey?’ she stammered. ‘Say—will a duck swim?’”

1917 J. C. Bridge, Cheshire Proverbs “He winks and thinks like a duck i' thunner.”

1933 A. Christie, Lord Edgware Dies “You did look for all the world like a dying duck in a thunderstorm.”

1960 C. Day Lewis, Buried Day “I had taken to vice like a duck to water, but it ran off me like water from a duck's back.”

1971 ‘A. Gilbert’, Tenant for Tomb “The Bear Lady said brightly that it was a nice day for the ducks.”
Content.Answer: duck - In phrases and proverbial sayings. duck's weather, fine day for ducks, etc., referring to wet weather; like a duck in thunder, like a (dying) duck in a thunderstorm: having a forlorn and hopeless appearance; like water off (or from) a duck's back, like (or as) a duck (takes) to water: easily, readily; does (or will, would) a duck swim?: a colloquial phrase of enthusiastic acceptance or confirmation.

duck

duck

duck

duck

1481 W. Caxton, Hist. Reynard Fox “They conne wel also duke in the water after lapwynches and dokys.”

1855 F. K. Robinson, Gloss. Yorks. Words “To Douk, to bathe or plunge under water, to duck.”

duck

1539 , Surrender of Monasteries “Dokkyng, Nodding and Beckynge.”

1599 T. Nashe, Lenten Stuffe “Douking on all foure vnto him.”

1608 S. Lennard, Of Wisdome “To ducke and stoop to all sorts of people.”

duck

duck

duck

1928 , Daily Express “You can frequently make the most of a suit by deliberately losing the first trick. This method of play, called ‘ducking’, is founded not only on the law of average probabilities but also on the expectation that the cards are normally distributed.”
Content.Answer: duck - transitive and intransitive. In the game of Bridge (see quots.).

Content.Question:
duck

1554 T. Sampson, “The fond nods, crosses, becks, and ducks.”

1637 J. Milton, Comus “Without duck or nod.”

1651 R. Brome, New Acad. “Be ready with your Napkin, and a lower douke maid.”

1802 C. Lamb, John Woodvil “The ducks, and nods Which weak minds pay to rank.”

1879 S. St. John, Life Sir J. Brooke “The ball rushing over our heads, caused a most undignified duck.”
Content.Answer:
duck - An instantaneous lowering of head or body; a rapid jerky bow or obeisance.
This is the main current sense
Content.SuperMemoReference: <H5 dir=ltr align=left><Font size="1" style="color: transparent"> SuperMemo Reference:</font><br><FONT class=reference>Title:"My Test Quote" <br>Source: Oxford English Dictionary

Content.Question:
duck

1836 C. J. Latrobe, “Two singular basins..not large enough for any monarch bigger than Oberon to take a duck in.”

1876 , World “The elder women content themselves with a few ducks as the waves break over them.”
Content.Answer: duck - A quick plunge, a dip.
Content.SuperMemoReference: <H5 dir=ltr align=left><Font size="1" style="color: transparent"> SuperMemo Reference:</font><br><FONT class=reference>Title:"My Test Quote" <br>Source: Oxford English Dictionary

Content.Question:
duck

1640 , Tables Rates & Duties “Duck hinderlands, middle good headlock.”

1660 , Act 12 Chas. II “Drilling & pack ducke ye 100 ells cont. 6 score.”

1780 T. Jefferson, Let. “What is to be done for tents, I know not. I am assured that very little duck can be got in this country.”

1834 F. Marryat, Jacob Faithful “A shirt of coarse duck.”

1883 T. Hardy, Longman's Mag. “The genuine white smock-frock of Russia duck and the whity-brown one of drabbet, are rarely seen now afield.”
Content.Answer:
duck - A strong untwilled linen (or later, cotton) fabric, lighter and finer than canvas; used for small sails and men's (esp. sailors') outer clothing.
This is the main current sense
Content.SuperMemoReference: <H5 dir=ltr align=left><Font size="1" style="color: transparent"> SuperMemo Reference:</font><br><FONT class=reference>Title:"My Test Quote" <br>Source: Oxford English Dictionary

Content.Question:
ducks

1825 , Universal Songster “T'other day I saw a goose in white ducks.”

1829 Miss Sheridan, Lett. etc. Dk. Somerset “The boys were in white ducks, with lightish green jackets.”

1849 W. M. Thackeray, Pendennis “They must be young Pendennis's white ducks.”
Content.Answer: ducks - plural. Trousers of this material.

Content.Question:
duck

1943 , War Illustr. “‘Ducks’ they are called in soldier slang, and it is easy to see why. In the first place there is something duck-like about these queer motor-barges-cum-trucks which are as much at home on the sea as on the land; and then their factory serial letters placed together spell ‘Dukws’.”

1944 , Hansard Commons “The marvellous American invention, the ‘Duck’, spelt D.U.K.W., is a heavy lorry which goes at between 40 and 50 miles per hour along the road, and can plunge into the water and swim out for miles to sea in quite choppy weather.”

1945 , Manch. Guardian “Officially known as ‘Dukws’—a combination of the factory serial letters D for boat, U for lorry body, and KW for lorry chassis—they quickly became known in the Army and Navy as ‘Ducks’.”

1945 , Ann. Reg. 1944 “‘Ducks’, amphibious lorries which were equally at home on land and in the water.”

1958 , Observer “Supply craft might stand offshore and disgorge their cargoes into ducks and other smaller craft.”
Content.Answer:
duck - An amphibious vehicle (see quots.).
This is the main current sense
